    },
    {
      "id": "fc3719e41b1e554de7fb0c62530fa3e38120e2a6",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 353,
        "name": "Li Dongyang",
        "email": "dongyangli@ddn.com",
        "username": "lidongyang"
      },
      "date": "2025-06-11 04:50:53.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nAndreas, a way to walkaround this bug and without adding the kernel patch is to limit the bio vecs to never go larger than max_segments reported from the device when allocating bio in osd_do_bio(), but I don't like the idea.\nJust want to mention if we absolutely don't want any new kernel patches, there's a possible way.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "5b3b20107b09d4860339b243014c16b767ff980f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2025-06-11 06:21:46.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nMy preference would be to not have a kernel patch. The previous change is just removing the kernel patches for T10-PI, and now this is adding a kernel patch back, which undoes the benefit of the previous work. \n\nWhat is the implication of having the smaller request size?  Does that hurt performance?  Can the workaround be limited to kernel versions that are affected, so that it goes away eventually?  My assumption is that having the workaround is not harmful for \"fixed\" kernels, so getting the version check slightly wrong is not a problem...",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "29f43a029f54eb3bd5202f567bccc0870e3353eb",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 683,
        "name": "jenkins",
        "email": "devops@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jenkins",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2025-06-11 08:17:11.000000000",
