      },
      "date": "2025-06-11 08:21:45.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nThe following sessions will be run for build 114202 patch 1\n\nEnforced:\n- review-ldiskfs-dne on el8.10-x86_64/ldiskfs servers and clients\n- review-ldiskfs-dne on el9.5-x86_64/ldiskfs servers and clients\n\nMaloo Test Queue: https://testing.whamcloud.com/test_queue?jobs=lustre-reviews&builds=114202&commit=Apply+Filter\nMaloo Results: https://testing.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/related?jobs=lustre-reviews&builds=114202#redirect",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "9d00780036c2094504ead81248b60bf4f6f356fe",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2025-06-11 13:20:35.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Verified+1\n\nPassed enforced test review-ldiskfs-dne on RHEL 8.10 / x86_64 uploaded by Trevis Autotest from trevis-93vm1: https://testing.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/f1cf146f-f315-48bd-9933-93d599a67677 ran 5 tests.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "e8108e48f053e6b4f874b543e5adae3e2625c813",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 353,
        "name": "Li Dongyang",
        "email": "dongyangli@ddn.com",
        "username": "lidongyang"
      },
      "date": "2025-06-12 01:35:53.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> Patch Set 1:\n> \n> My preference would be to not have a kernel patch. The previous change is just removing the kernel patches for T10-PI, and now this is adding a kernel patch back, which undoes the benefit of the previous work. \n> \n> What is the implication of having the smaller request size?  Does that hurt performance?  Can the workaround be limited to kernel versions that are affected, so that it goes away eventually?  My assumption is that having the workaround is not harmful for \"fixed\" kernels, so getting the version check slightly wrong is not a problem...\n\nI took a closer look and limiting the segments/number of bio_vec is only part of it,\nbio_split could still happen if bio size is bigger than max_sectors from the queue limit as well.\nIt still feels wrong to construct the bio in osd and make sure it won't get split: upper layers should be able to submit a large bio and it's up to block layer to do the splitting if necessary, osd should not worry about bio splitting.\n\nAlso this kernel patch is an upstream fix, unlike the T10-PI patches removed previous which are custom and never going to make upstream, and it only affects rocky9.1 to 9.5, due to the changes of multipage bio_vec.\n\nI marked this is just optional because the bug triggers when the nvme device supports T10PI *and* it's max_segments smaller than 256, in real world deployments we are more likely to see\ndevices with max_segments way over 256, like 2048.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "e56363ac27fbb5ab1a516582a4a1944b0b40f41a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2025-06-12 04:33:12.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1\n\nIf the patches have a limited lifetime then it isn't so bad. We are already on el9.5 testing for most branches, and el9.6 will follow closely behind.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
